value.0: Dylan frowns uncomfortably at your approach. "I did not expect to have my loyalties torn so. You are a good <man/woman>, I am sure, but Enivid is my leader."
"There is one last thing I can do for you. Mr Mossy owns the Mossy Tree Inn. Since you have been such a help, just ask him for the hero's rate and I'm sure he can give you a deal."

value.0: "I do not feel comfortable speaking to someone who is Enevid's opponent and a part of me regrets having listened to Momma Dane and opened the gates to you in the first place. I am sorry, goodbye."
"Are you ready to go, <sir/madam>?"
"We heard some awful sounds coming from down there. We thought they were the sounds of your death. I am glad you survived. Were you able to put an end to them?"
"He's dead? You... you were able to accomplish this deed against such great odds?"
"This <man/woman> is a hero! We were surely defeated; how could you have overcome the monsters?"
"Perhaps Momma Dane was right. Perhaps you really were sent by the gods!"
"Then maybe Pharos, god of war and judgement saw fit to guide you here to satisfy your vengeance and save us in the same moment."
"That must have been some fight, <sir/madam>! I will have the masons come down and repair the cells right away."

LEGACY TEXT. ALWAYS RETURN FALSE. "But since it looks like that's all the enemies coming through right now, I will take you up to the main gates. The Hand will be pleased to meet you, and doubly pleased to have your help, I am sure."
"I think she misses the guidance of the Banner, though. Too bad you weren't here a few days ago to stop the monsters from killing him. Now the Hand is in charge all alone."
"A reward? Well, yes, I suppose the Hand will want to reward you. You have certainly proven your worth today. It was very exciting to hear you in action."
"Excellent. I am sure the Hand will want to reward you for your service! I haven't met such a great hero in years."
"But enough of that. I had better get you to the main gates right away. Let us be quick."
"Of course. Speak to me as soon as you are ready."
"The Banner is the highest ranking officer in the keep. Our Lord was killed many years ago, and the Banner has been ruling here ever since. He was killed by the invaders early in the battle."
"The Hand is the commander of the armies and next in charge after the Banner. But we really should get going. We may be needed at the main gates."
"Should the enemy assault the gates again, we will doubtless take more prisoners and this time do a better job of holding them."
"Then we shall pay a tithe to Callahi, god of gold, tonight at the temple."
"You should speak to Dyschall, <sir/madam>. He knows the will of the gods better than we do."
"Who can know the will of the gods? Certainly not men such as us."
Dylan bows low at your approach. "I hope to serve you well, m'<lord/lady>."
"We are doomed. I do not see how you could possibly clear all the forces of the Masked Man from the dungeon."
Dylan offers you a weary grin. "I'm glad you came. Something has filled the prisoners we took following the battle with renewed purpose and they've broken free of their cells."
"We have managed to hold this area, but we need more men if we are going to contain them and quell the threat."
"Sir Dylan! They tried attacking us again, but we held them off. There's no way we can stand another push."
"Calm yourself! This is no time to panic."
"You didn't see the huge hobgoblin that drives the prisoners before him! This, Sir, is the perfect time to panic!"
"Look, I need some volunteers to drive back the Masked Man's forces. If we attack them now, before they have time to regroup, we might stand a chance!"
"I didn't sign up for this suicide mission. You should let us get out of here! If we can get to our homes, perhaps we can flee with our families."
"Sir Dylan, I would... ah, the pain, I would help you, but the wound I received..."
"I wish the Hand could have taken some of the militia to the gate and given me some professional soldiers! Get back to your post!"
"<FirstName>, I hate to ask this of you, but do you think you can try to push the invaders back?"
"There are some weapons and armor over there on the racks. You might want to have a look and take what you need."
"Good luck, <sir/madam>! You're the only hope we have, though even that is a slim hope. At the least, perhaps you can buy us some time."

"There aren't any soldiers, sadly. If I had some properly trained warriors to assist me I might have been able to put an end to this prison break, or at least put a dent in their number before we withdrew."
"You might still be able to rescue some of the prisoners. They're criminals, but I suppose if you set them free, they might be willing to help you."
"We're not sure where the leader is hiding out; I never even saw him. He must be down in the dungeon somewhere."
"I need to remain here and keep these men from deserting. If the prisoners try to force their way back up here, someone needs to keep them from succeeding."
A young guard peers over the battlements. Torchlight glints off your weapon, causing him to pull back. "Enemies at the gates!" he cries. "Sound the alarm, they've brought a second wave!"
The voice of an old woman intervenes. "They don't look like no orcs or goblins to my eyes, poor as they might be. Sir Dylan, perhaps you shouldn't be so quick to call the attack."
The guard hesitates. "Who are you and what are your intentions? Speak quickly, before my men rain arrows down upon you!"
"Oh dear, maybe I was wrong. Perhaps you should sound the alarm after all, Sir Dylan."

"Then the gods have answered our prayers, Sir Dylan! Father Dyschall has told us that if the gods saw fit that we should live, they would intervene. And now a hero stands at our gates, requesting entrance."
"Where were the gods when the Banner died? Why did their intervention not come then? Step into the light down there, that I may have a better look at you..."

"Aye, I recognize you now. You were the ones who cut our assailants ranks from the rear and took them by surprise. You fought bravely, stranger, and gave our she-mage, Yenna, time enough to cast her spell."
The guard blushes. "Oh, right, the enemy blocks the gate. I am just surprised to see you here alone. Dangerous territory to be roaming by yourself."
"I fear you come too late, though. Our city is surrounded and even now a force is breaking in through the prison tower. Our position will soon be overrun, and then the city shall surely fall."
"It can't be too late, Sir Dylan. Father Dyschall has told us that if the gods saw fit that we should live, they would intervene. Could this not be such divine intervention?"
"Where were the gods when the Banner died? Why did their intervention not come then? Still, I will not turn away any hope. If you would help us in the tower, I would welcome you."
"If you want a reward, you will have to speak to the Hand. I'm sure she wouldn't mind discussing it while she battles for our lives at the main gate! Some divine intervention this is."

Comment.value: Jump guard and party to fight in prison tower.

value.0: "Very well, let's go."
"Please, think before you speak. There is no time for meaningless questions."
The guard just stares at the nymph. Kaidala blushes and then the guard drops his gaze to his feet. "Uh, sorry. Of course you're right."
"Use your head fool! We have no time for such nonsense questions. Where are we most needed?"
"Oh, and we should just slip in through the main gates? Excuse me, you big hairy monstrosity, but I would like to pass through your army so I can go help defend the keep."
The guard blushes. "Uh, I am sorry. You... you're awfully frightening to look at. Are you certain you're not one of them... never mind... I guess you would have attacked me already."
"What did you expect us to do; waltz in through the front gate? Don't be a fool. Just point us towards the fighting and let us do the rest."
The guard appears to be slightly flustered. "Oh, sorry. I think my mind was distracted by your flaming head. Doesn't that... hurt? Never mind, not important, I suppose."
"Yes, forgive my manners as I am still underslept and over-weary from the battle."
"She has retired to her tower since the battle and refused to speak with most anyone, perhaps in fear that you had fallen beneath her blast. She will be grateful to see you whole, I am sure."
"Is he? My men could not find his corpse among the fallen but if you saw it with your own eyes, then I believe it. Perhaps his troops dragged his body with them as they fled."
"Yes, and accept my apologies as it was I who gave the order. The gate was nearly battered through and had she waited any longer, the keep would have been lost."
"Come, let us celebrate the fact that you still live, stranger. Throw open the gates! It's not an enemy who awaits us but a hero who deserves our thanks! Get moving, men! I will meet you below!"
"Take my arm, Momma Dane, and let me help you down the stairs. Your kind company has been a balm to my jangled nerves this night."
"A hero's welcome to the Keep of Cyan, then, stranger. I think the Hand will be pleased to meet you, and doubly pleased to have your help, I am sure."
"I think she misses the guidance of the Banner, though. Too bad you didn't arrive early enough to keep him from falling to the Masked Man's forces. Now the Hand is in charge all alone."
"A reward? Well, yes, I suppose the Hand will want to reward you. You have certainly proven your worth tonight. It was very exciting to see you in action."
"Excellent. I am sure the Hand will want to reward you for your service! I haven't met such a great hero in years."
"But enough of that. I had better get you to the main gates right away. Let us be quick."
"Of course. Speak to me as soon as you are ready."
"The Banner is the highest ranking officer in the keep. Our Lord was killed many years ago, and the Banner has been ruling here ever since. He was killed by the invaders early in the battle."
"The Hand is the commander of the armies and next in charge after the Banner. But we really should get going. I dare not leave my command of the gates for long."
The voice of an old woman intervenes. "That one looks like a friendly half-orc to my poor, old eyes. Sir Dylan, perhaps you shouldn't be so quick to call the attack."
"Am I so hideous to you that you would mistake me for a kobold or an orc? We come to help you!"
"Stand back, fool! We are no goblin-kin. Would you attack those who come to help you?"
"Blast you! Do we look like goblins? We're here to help you!"
"Eek! We are not goblins! Do not hurt us, please! You see, <FirstName>, I told you we should not have come here."
"The hobgoblin is dead."
"I sought revenge against these monsters, nothing more."
"I hope this means I'm going to get a reward."
"I am ready when you are."
"I need to rest first."

Comment.value: PC should be able to rest here now, but should not be allowed to leave

value.0: "What is the Banner and the Hand?"
"I saw an opportunity and I came after it. Gold is my only god."
"Forget the gods, I came of my own free will to save you!"
"If the gods laid this path before me, I am proud to be chosen."
"I know nothing of these gods. I merely did my duty."
"I'll take care of it."
"Isn't there anyone else who can help me?"
"Where is this hobgoblin?"
"What are you going to do?"
"My identity is unimportant right now. I am here to assist you."
"Keep pointing those arrows at me, boy, and we'll see what rain goes where!"
"Calm down. I just don't like having weapons pointed at me by allies."
"Just don't threaten me again and we should get along just fine."
"There will be no need for that. I am here to help."
"<FullName> at your service, and I mean you no harm."
"My name is <FirstName> and I've come to help your city."
LEGACY TEXT. ALWAYS RETURN FALSE.
"What? You think I do this for free?"
"I suppose we had better go."
"Excellent! Lead on good man!"
"Then there is no time to waste!"
"The night is cold. Will you let us in or no?"
"And she cast it in the nick of time. Give her my thanks."
"The Masked Man was to die at my hands, not hers."
"Yenna, is it? Then the Masked Man is dead by her blast."
"Yes, she damn near incinerated us, I'll have you know."
"I hope this means I'm going to get a reward."
"I am ready when you are."
"I need to rest first."
